ce:section.ce:para:
To achieve the rapid detection of food hazards, a variety of fluorescent strategies have been developed based on the specific recognition of antibodies (Chen et al., 2019; 
                     Wang et al., 2019; Zhang et al., 2017). However, antibodies are usually complicated to prepare, whose binding properties are easily affected by synthesis batches and temperature, limiting their application in constructing fluorescent sensor. The aptamer is a functional single-stranded DNA or RNA that can specifically recognize the target, obtained through the screening of exponentially enriched ligand system evolution technology (SELEX) (Ellington and Szostak, 1990; Tuerk and Gold, 1990). Due to the advantages of good stability, easy synthesis and labelling, strong specificity and affinity, aptamers have made good progress in detecting small molecules like pesticides in food analysis (Liu et al., 2020). Currently, our group used aptamers as recognition molecules for pesticides to construct a series of colorimetric and fluorescent sensors, which can quickly and visually detect pesticide residues such as isocarbophos (Chen et al., 2017), acetamiprid (Wang et al., 2018; Yang et al., 2017), and paraquat (Ran and Wu, 2019) in foods and agricultural products. In 2017, the specific aptamer with a high affinity to carbendazim (named CZ-13) was firstly screened and successfully applied to establish an electrochemical aptasensor (Eissa and Zourob, 2017). Recently, several aptasensors for carbendazim detection have been successfully established based on electrochemical, colorimetric and fluorescent methods (Shi et al., 2022; Su et al., 2020; 
                     Wang et al., 2021; Wang et al., 2020; Zhao et al., 2020). Among them, fluorescent aptasensor has elicited tremendous interest of researchers due to their low background signal, high sensitivity and fast speed. Although the reported fluorescent aptasensors usually display outstanding performance, they often use environmentally toxic substances and expensive sensing materials (e.g. Rhodamine B, SYBR Green I, FAM) as fluorescence sources. Hence, there is an urgent need for an environmentally friendly and economical aptasensor for the rapid detection of carbendazim.
